SOLUTION:
To get the relative pose, we need to compute two things:

The pose to be composed with poseR1 to get poseR2.   It means that we need to get the "pose_inc" that satisfy with this equality
tcomp(psoeR1,**pose_inc**) = poseR2

The next code compute that relative pose that allows to poseR1 reach poseR2
% Computing the relative pose between R1 and R2

% pose to be composed with poseR1 to reach poseR2

pose_inc = tcomp(tinv(poseR1),poseR2);

The covariance matrix of the relative pose. The uncertainty of R1 after reach the position poseR2
    c = cos(poseR1(3)); s = sin(poseR1(3));

    x_1 = poseR1(1); y_1 = poseR1(2);

    x_2 = poseR2(1); y_2 = poseR2(2);

    % Jacobians to compute the covariance of the relative pose
    JacF_1 = [-c -s -(x_2-x_1)*s+(y_2-y_1)*c ;
               s -c -(x_2-c_1)*c-(y_2-y_1)*s ;
               0 0 -1];
    JacF_2 = [c   s 0;
              -s  c 0;
               0 0 1];
    % Computing the covariance of the relative pose
    C_p12 = JacF_1*co1*JacF_1' + JacF_2*co2*JacF_2';`


Roughly,
JacF_1 is a jacobian that define how difference poseR1 is against pose_inc
JacF_2 is a jacobian that define how difference poseR2 is against pose_inc
C_p12 is the covariance matrix of R1 after move to poseR2

